                    <locus target="#133r #133v"/>: One page from the <title type="complete" ref="LIT1113Anqasa"/> from another copy of the same book
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a04">
                    <desc>
                    <locus target="#iir(ecto)"/>": Title Page.  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ዳዊት፡ ዘተኀትመ፡ በብሔረ፡ ሮሜ፡ በ፲ወ፱፻ወ፬ ዓመተ፡ ምሕረት፡ ዘአኅተሞ፡ አፈወርቅ፡ ገብረ፡ ኢየሱስ፡ ዘብሔረ፡ ዘጌ፡</foreign> Roma, Tipografia Poliglotta Vaticana, 1913
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a05">
                    <desc type="Record">
                    <locus target="#130v"/>: Record of land transaction on Gənbot 16, 1916 EC
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a06">
                    <desc>
                    <locus target="#153v #154r"/>: Colophon: This book belongs to Lǝj Abay (baptismal name is deleted), son of Ato Wäldä Maryam, whose baptismal name is Wäldä Śǝllase . . . . It is written in the year of Matthew, the Evangelist, in 1917 EC [= 1924–5], when Empress Zewditu, daughter of Menilek was Emperor [sic] of Ethiopia, and along with her the regent, his Highness, Ras Täfäri; and our prince is Wag Šum Käbädä and our archbishop is Abba Matewos from the throne of Mark, the Apostle.  The scribe is Aläqa Dǝnqayähu, whose baptismal name is Gäbrä Ṣadǝq. Praise to God and to his mother, the Virgin Mary forever and ever, Amen and Amen
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e01">
                    <desc>
                    <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iv(erso) #iiv(erso) #ivv(erso) #129v #130r #134r #154v #155r #155v #156r #156v"/>: blank
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e02">
                    <desc>
                    Identified in the insurance hand list as Psalter 23
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e03">
                    <desc>
                    Psalm 118 contains the spiritual meanings of the Hebrew letters
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e04">
                    <desc>
                    Scribal intervention: text has been removed (<locus target="#153r"/>)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
